been his home for most of the twentieth century. Witty, urbane, and always entertaining, Berger describes the music scene in New York and Boston since the 1930s, discussing the heady days when he was a member of a tight-knit circle of avant-garde young composers mentored by Aaron Copland as well as his participation in a group at Harvard University dedicated to Stravinsky. As Virgil Thomson's associate on the New York Herald Tribune and founding editor of the prestigious Perspectives of New Music, Berger became one of the preeminent observers and critics of American music. His reflections on the role of music in contemporary life, his journalism career, and how changes in academia influence the composition and teaching of music offer a unique perspective informed by Berger's abundant intelligence and experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMusiczUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  a1930s.  a20th century.  aaaron copland.  aamerican composers.  aamerican music.  aart scene.  aautobiography.  aavant garde music.  abiography.  aboretz.  aboston.  acommunism.  acomposers.  aconductor.  aessays.  amalkin conservatory.  amemoir.  amodernism.  amusic composition.  amusic criticism.  amusic history.  amusic theory.  amusic.  amusicians.  anationalism.  anew york.  anonfiction.  apiano variations.  apopular culture.  ared scare.  aschoenberg.  ashort symphony.  astatements.  astravinsky.  awpa.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023251840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092821340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520928213423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520928213/original  a978-3-11-069